          }}></path></svg></a>{`Reliability and security`}</h3>
    <p>{`The managed configuration for the Warthog gateway is exposed through `}<a parentName="p" {...{
        "href": "https://cloud.google.com/storage"
      }}>{`Google Cloud Storage`}</a>{`. For all API keys, the Warthog Graph Manager provisions a public file accessible via the hash of the API key. In the event that managed configuration is inaccessible due to an outage in Google's Cloud Storage service, the gateway will continue to serve the last-known configuration. In the event that Warthog Graph Manager API is down, changes to managed configuration will be stalled but the last-published configuration files will still be accessible via GCS.`}</p>
    <h3 {...{
      "id": "using-variants-to-control-rollout"
    }}><a parentName="h3" {...{
        "href": "#using-variants-to-control-rollout",
        "aria-label": "using variants to control rollout permalink",
        "className": "anchor"
      }}><svg parentName="a" {...{
          "aria-hidden": "true",
          "focusable": "false",
          "height": "16",
          "version": "1.1",
          "viewBox": "0 0 16 16",
          "width": "16"
        }}><path parentName="svg" {...{
            "fillRule": "evenodd",
            "d": "M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z"
          }}></path></svg></a>{`Using variants to control rollout`}</h3>
    <p>{`With `}<a parentName="p" {...{
        "href": "#managed-configuration"
      }}>{`managed federation`}</a>{`, you have the ability to control which version of your graph a fleet of gateways are running with. For the majority of deployments, rolling over all of your gateways to a new schema version is a good strategy, since changes should be checked to be backwards compatible using `}<a parentName="p" {...{
        "href": "/platform/schema-validation/"
      }}>{`schema validation`}</a>{`. However, changes at the gateway level may involve a variety of different updates, like transferring type ownership from one service to another. In the case that your infrastructure requires more advanced deployment strategies, we recommend using `}<a parentName="p" {...{
        "href": "/platform/schema-registry/#registering-schemas-to-a-variant"
      }}>{`graph variants`}</a>{` to manage different fleets of gateways running with different configurations.`}</p>
    <p>{`For instance, in order to have a canary deployment, you might maintain two production graphs in the graph manager, one called `}<code parentName="p" {...{
        "className": "language-text"
      }}>{`prod`}</code>{` and one called `}<code parentName="p" {...{
        "className": "language-text"
      }}>{`prod-canary`}</code>{`. Your deployment of a change to some federated service named "foo" might look something like this:`}</p>
    <ol>
      <li parentName="ol">{`Check changes in "foo" against `}<code parentName="li" {...{
          "className": "language-text"
        }}>{`prod`}</code>{` and `}<code parentName="li" {...{
          "className": "language-text"
        }}>{`prod-canary`}</code>{`:`}<div parentName="li" {...{
          "className": "gatsby-highlight",
          "data-language": "text"
        }}><pre parentName="div" {...{
            "style": {
              "counterReset": "linenumber NaN"
            },
            "className": "language-text line-numbers"
          }}><code parentName="pre" {...{
              "className": "language-text"
            }}>{`warthog service:check --tag=prod --serviceName=foo && warthog service:check --tag=prod-canary --serviceName=foo`}</code><span parentName="pre" {...{
              "aria-hidden": "true",
              "className": "line-numbers-rows",
              "style": {
                "whiteSpace": "normal",
                "width": "auto",
                "left": "0"
              }
            }}><span parentName="span"></span></span></pre></div></li>
      <li parentName="ol">{`Deploy changes to "foo" into your production environment. (`}<em parentName="li">{`Note: This will not roll out changes to the gateway yet`}</em>{`)`}</li>
      <li parentName="ol">{`Roll over the `}<code parentName="li" {...{
          "className": "language-text"
        }}>{`prod-canary`}</code>{` graph, containing one gateway container, using `}<code parentName="li" {...{
          "className": "language-text"
        }}>{`warthog service:push --tag=prod-canary --serviceName=foo`}</code>{`. (`}<em parentName="li">{`Note: If composition fails due to intermediate changes to the canary graph, new configuration will not be rolled out`}</em>{`)`}</li>
      <li parentName="ol">{`Wait for health checks to pass against the canary, watch dashboards, etc.`}</li>
      <li parentName="ol">{`After the canary is stable, roll out the changes to the rest of production using `}<code parentName="li" {...{
          "className": "language-text"
        }}>{`warthog service:push --tag=prod --serviceName=foo`}</code>{`.`}</li>
    </ol>
    <p>{`Because you can `}<a parentName="p" {...{
        "href": "/platform/schema-registry/#associating-metrics-with-a-variant"
      }}>{`tag metrics with variants`}</a>{` as well, you can use `}<a parentName="p" {...{
        "href": "https://engine.warthog.dev"
      }}>{`Warthog Graph Manager`}</a>{` to verify a canary's performance before rolling out changes to the rest of the graph. You can also use a similar strategy with variants to support a variety of other advanced deployment workflows, like blue/green deployments.`}</p>
